Raw dev notes -- Side Project Juggling: AI Metrics vs. Extension Maintenance

Okay, so this past week has been a pretty good snapshot of the two very different worlds my side projects live in. On one hand, I'm deep in the weeds of AI evaluation, and on the other, I'm playing whack-a-mole with website changes for a browser extension. It's a constant juggle, but that's what keeps things interesting, right?

First up, the RAG pipeline project. This is my ongoing experiment with building a robust system for querying my own documents, specifically those with a lot of bidirectional text (think Hebrew/English mixed). The goal is to have a smart assistant that can pull relevant info from my personal knowledge base, and the "bidi-doc" part adds a whole layer of complexity to embeddings and retrieval.

This week, the big win was finally getting a solid search acceptance test in place. I spent a good chunk of time crafting 18 specific queries across 5 different categories, trying to cover the common use cases and edge cases for my document set. It's not just about throwing queries at it; it's about defining what "good" retrieval looks like. The target was a hit@5 of 80% – meaning for 80% of queries, the correct answer should be in the top 5 results. Getting there wasn't trivial. It involved a bit of tweaking the embedding model, adjusting chunking strategies, and even refining the prompt for the retriever. There's a real art to setting up these evaluations, and it felt good to finally see the numbers hit the mark. It's a small step, but it gives me confidence that the core retrieval mechanism is actually working as intended, which is huge for a RAG system. It's easy to get lost in the hype, but having concrete metrics like this grounds the work.

Then there's the browser extension, SmartHebrewRTL. This little guy is a passion project to make the web a better place for Hebrew speakers, fixing RTL display issues on various sites. It's a constant battle against the ever-changing DOM. This week, it was `Claude.ai`'s turn. They must have pushed an update that completely broke my selectors for injecting the RTL fixes. Ugh. It's always a bit of a detective game: open up dev tools, poke around, find the new class names or element structures, update the JavaScript, and push a new version. It's not glamorous work, but it's essential to keep the extension functional for its users. Bumping to v2.2.4 felt less like an exciting new feature and more like a necessary maintenance chore. It's a reminder that building something is only half the battle; keeping it alive and relevant is the other, often more tedious, half.

It's funny how these two types of work contrast. One is about deep, analytical problem-solving and metric-driven improvement in a cutting-edge field. The other is about quick, reactive fixes to keep a utility tool from breaking. Both are rewarding in their own way. The RAG work feels like I'm pushing my understanding of AI, while the extension work is a constant lesson in web resilience and user-focused maintenance. It's a good balance, I think, preventing me from getting too bogged down in one type of challenge. It also highlights how much I enjoy building things that *work* and are useful, whether it's for myself or for a small group of users.

Next up: Expanding the RAG test set and monitoring for more extension breakage.
